chapters.title: Pivoting Strategy and Product-Market Fit Journey
Reflection on Engineering Background and Analytics Approach

lines.text: Welcome everyone to the third episode of the zero to community podcast where we showcase the stories of founders and marketers who have built their own communities around their company's products or services from scratch.
And on our third episode, we have Chris, who's the founder of Meander, which is an AI talent talent
sorry.
Let me get that again.
Well, this is what the ad thing is for.
And for our third episode, we have Chris, who's the founder and CEO of Meander, which is a AI powered talent acquisition service.
For the audience, Chris, can you tell us about yourself and about Meander?
Sure.
Yeah.
So hi, everyone.

I am building a platform that helps with recruiting using AI and process improvement really to identify some of the challenges that that I faced in my last role before starting this company in twenty twenty one.
I was a a senior leader in the recruiting organization at Wayfair.
We recruited thousands of people, and I got to see some of the challenges at scale and felt like a lot of it could be done more effectively.

Previously, my career had worked in supply chain and earlier in my career in aerospace engineering, where I worked on some of the implementation of unmanned systems and unmanned aircraft and kind of saw some of the challenges in terms of regulation and technical work there and felt like, you know, the TA and HR space is kinda ripe for innovation right now.
And I'm pretty excited to be working in this space and actually building kind of products that I think solve some of the big challenges that I think really exist out there.
Awesome.
Now can you tell us, like, who uses Meander?
Like, who's the persona for, you know, talent acquisition as a service?
Yeah.
So it's changed quite a bit, I think, over the the journey.
I think initially, I was working with TA leaders who were looking up for ways to optimize their recruiting process and actually get more productivity out of each individual recruiter.
And so we looked at kind of ways to optimize top of funnel recruiting.

I think what we found more recently is outreach from earlier stage founders that are trying to do a lot of the recruiting process themselves because they either don't have the budget or the time or or really the kind of interest to hire a big recruiting team, and maybe they've worked with agencies that haven't really helped solve their recruiting challenges.
So what we're really trying to do now is empower individuals on the business side to to run their own recruiting process.
And so, generally, that's founders or exec level people at early stage companies before they have that ability to build their own in house HR and TA team.
Absolutely.
Well, those seem like two fairly different segments.
So can you tell us, like, how you got from or how you went about kind of looking at those two segments and shifting from the first to the second?
Yeah.
I'd say, um, the journey has been a lot of, like, test and evaluation.

So, you know, I initially started with this hypothesis that, uh, the person that would wanna buy this kind of products would be the people that I was working very closely with, these kind of heads of talent acquisition who were running large teams of recruiters.
You know, we had over four hundred recruiters on the team, and my job was to help optimize the whole recruiting process.
I also had a thirty person recruiting team of my own that I was managing and, you know, looking at ways to improve.
And so the initial hypothesis was that this kind of tool that I was building would add a lot of value to those individuals.
And so a lot of the initial outreach and engagement and experimentation was really focused there.

But what I what I actually found is as we were running those experiments, I was getting some kind of market pull in demand from others who kinda saw what I was doing and actually got it very quickly without really me really kind of communicating that value prop to them and kinda asked me to help out with some of the processes.
And so I kinda, like, shifted a little bit.

I was kind of still in the kind of pre pre product market fit phase, and so I felt that having that demand pull from the market in a different direction was a good signal that maybe there was more opportunity in a different area, but also kind of that tied in with the, I think, changing external market dynamics where we had slowdown in hiring within the tech industry, which is where I was focused.
And so all of a sudden, large tech was not hiring in volume, which is what my initial product was designed to optimize for.
But it was more about hiring the right people and and making sure that the interview process was filtering out those that would be a a poor fit.

And so I think the the kind of the the strategy of the business and the product roadmap changed as we learned more about who was actually asking for the the product that we were building, and then how could we adapt what we had already done in order to serve those customers.
So it's, you know, very much a kind of like lean start up, test, measure, improve, evaluate, pivot, persevere kind of approach.
That's amazing.
It's great.
I think I've never I've only felt that kind of market pull once in my own company and my god, it's fantastic when you do kind of feel that.
And well, I guess, for the context of the audience that that we have today, I think what they might be especially interested in is, like, the content part of this.
So I know that you make content.
Can you tell us about, like, the kind of content that that you put out and why you got started with content?
Yeah.
So I guess right now, there's kind of four main channels of content marketing I do.
The main one is is kinda LinkedIn, starting to grow in in YouTube with a YouTube channel we run.
And then also do email marketing and have a blog that I kind of post different content up to.
I'd say the the kind of email marketing and the blog are probably less front and center just based on the experimentation that I've done.
LinkedIn and and and YouTube seems to gather a lot more engagement, actually lead to a lot more potential leads that will hopefully turn into customers at some point in the pipeline.
Okay.
And then how did you get started with kinda what was the original motivation for for getting started?
Was that something you started from day one?
And then, like, what was the initial target?
Was it, you know, were you building content for people specifically in talent acquisition, or was this already when you were looking at, say, founders?
Yeah.
I'd say going into starting this company, I had no real experience with marketing, and I didn't quite appreciate the power of marketing.

And so I went in with the kind of the traditional kind of MBA entrepreneurship path where you interview a bunch of customers, you build products for those customers, and you get them to buy it, and then you kinda, like, iterate over that that approach.
And as I was going through that process, I got some really good feedback.
I got a lot of kind of warm connections on the phone.

And when I was asking for ideas and and customer interviews, I found that, you know, a lot of people were willing to give their time, but they actually weren't necessarily converting into customers until unless it was someone that I knew knew already knew knew closely and knew had the kind of problem that I was I was solving.
But what I found was was interesting is I posted a little bit about the product that I was building on LinkedIn in the early early days of the the launch.

And I actually got a lot of interest from people that even outside of my network just kind of reaching out organically through InMails and asking me a little bit more about what I was building and whether they could participate in any kind of pilot or upcoming trial, which led me to believe that this was a channel that I had, you know, completely overlooked.

And then as I was getting close to the launch process, I kinda started with with the, I think, the more traditional, like, cold outbound email campaign, you know, signed up for a CRM and and an automation service, looked at best practices, read a bunch of books, and then tried to figure out how do I kind of find cold leads, get the message out to to them, and then potentially convert them.
And I ran an experiment for several months to to, you know, to see what the kind of conversion rate was gonna be like on that cold outbound.
And even as I was doing that, I wasn't really focusing on the content marketing side of things.
I found that the called outbound yielded, I think, zero actual conversions, but just the kind of very organic content that I was creating actually generated a few leads that turned into customers.
And and so without doing any work, it seemed like the content side was much more valuable.

And so as we kind of we initially were were planning to launch in the summer of twenty twenty two, but as we decided to put that launch on hold given the market changes and rethink the type of product that we needed to build, I then started to invest more in in content marketing to try and understand a little bit more about what is actually going on in the market, what are people interested in, what are they asking questions about, and started to then use content as a way to kinda test hypothesis in the market.

But instead of reaching out to maybe a hundred people or get warm instructions to a hundred people to get thirty customer interviews, I could post an idea and a hypothesis, and that would get in front of thousands of people.
And those that were actually interested would comment or like or potentially reach out to me privately, which is what happened a lot.
And so all of a sudden, I found this incredibly valuable channel to get feedback instantaneously without having to set up multiple phone calls.
And, know, you can you can then jump on a call with someone to learn a little bit more about the comment that they asked, but it's a warm introduction then.
And so the actual information that you get is much richer.
I mean, we we learn marketing one on one at business school, but how do you actually do that in a in a kind of a modern kind of SaaS business approach?
And how do you do it in a way that it actually converts people into paying customers at at the bottom of the funnel?

And so that was when I kind of started on this path of learning more about it, started to focus on how do I build an audience, how do I engage with more people, how do I define my my ICP so that I can actually target the people and write content for the people that are most relevant to the business that I'm building?
And that kind of just snowballed from there really.

And, you know, the last two years, I've been kind of experimenting as with the product test testing and iterating figure out what messages resonate and generally a good I found to be a good leading indicator of where I should take the product road map.
So it's become kind of fully integrated, especially as a solo founder now where I developed.
Yeah.
Absolutely.
Well, I guess reflecting on on my own journey.
I'm I'm just starting out.
Though I think one thing we have in common, you know, just for context for people who don't know, Chris and I were both as you know, we we met when we were doing our MBA at MIT.
And I think MIT was interesting in that there was especially an interesting focus on the intersection of business and kind of engineering.
I think we both have an engineering background.
So Mhmm.
That's something I'm thinking about as well.
I think that's resonating is, like, that analytics piece of what's working and what's not.

And I think where it intersects with business is not just you have to kind of combine both, like, the high level numbers as well as kind of thinking about personas and and of what your audience is thinking about.
But I think you you you seem to be doing a a fairly good job.
So something to aspire to as I go through my journey with making content.
And hopefully, others as well.
If they're listening, presumably, they're thinking about making their own kind of content for their company.

I guess on on on that, you know, do you have any other thoughts or recommendations for someone who might be thinking about right now making, you know, content as part of their, you know, content marketing strategy for for their company?
Yeah.
I mean, I I would say that if I was starting this all over again, I would define my persona first, and then the the kind of next thing I would do is say, okay.
What what are they searching for?
If they go on Google, what what questions are they asking?
And there's a lot of tools that actually help you to kinda dive into that in a little more detail.

But if you have the opportunity to talk to people and, you know, really understand that persona well, Doing a quick Google search for, you know, in my case, like, how do I build a recruiting capacity plan and see the type of content that's already produced there?
You could you could learn from that content, but also figure out where where are the unanswered questions and where can you add value.

And I think that the the journey for me has been more about, like, where can I, like, share what I know or or or uncover new information and make the lives of the persona, that target customer easier so that I can build more credibility and and kind of help people?
It's it's kinda like it's more about helping rather than selling Yeah.
With the content marketing side of things.
Absolutely.
Alright.
Wonderful.
Well, I guess, maybe to wrap up, if someone wants to, you know, reach out to you or I'll learn more about Miander, how can they do that?
Yeah.
So the the kind of content side is you can find me on on LinkedIn, Chris Manion.
It should be fairly easy to find out Chris Manion.
Meander is probably the easiest way to find me.
The YouTube channel, I I enjoy creating content there.
It's the channel is at recruiting analytics.
If you go on to YouTube, hopefully, you'll find some of the content there helpful Or just, you know, meander dot com oh, sorry.
Meander h q dot com is our website.
It's kind of going through a bit of an iteration right now, so it'll probably be very different in a in a few weeks time, but that's probably the the kind of best place to learn more about what I do.
But, you know, I'm on LinkedIn every day.
That's the kind of cool part of the business now.
So, yeah, I hope to kind of engage with more people on that.
Wonderful.
Sounds good.
I'll add those links in the description.
But, you know, thank you so much for taking the time.
Of course.
Yeah.
Thanks, Adam.
Wonderful.
Thanks, Adam.
Alright.
Take care.
